ce:section.ce:para:
According to reports, DNA plays an important role in bacterial proliferation, so it is urgent to study the state of E. coli’s DNA [45]. Because bacteria themselves have a self-healing function, only the severe destruction or loss of genomic DNA is the last fatal factor for the cell. In this work, Affinity Gel Electrophoresis (AGE) was used to study the leakage and damage of catalyst-treated DNA under visible light exposure [46]. After light irradiation treatments within 2-GQDs/NH2-MIL-125, the fluorescence intensity of DNA weakened from 0.5 h and disappeared almost completely after 2 h, indicating that the DNA was severely distorted (

                              Fig. S7

                           ). Based on the above results, we believe that the death of E. coli treated by GQDs/NH2-MIL-125 is due to cell membrane destruction caused by ROS produced by light and damage to biological macromolecules such as DNA.
